Below is a production-safe migration plan for Azure SQL to move 50M rows from an existing partitioned table to a new table, recreate all partitions and indexes dynamically, copy data in batches, then swap tables.
This approach avoids long blocking operations and works well for large financial/reporting tables.
Assume:
Plain text
Copy code
Old table: dbo.cff_report
Partition column: report_date
New table: dbo.cff_report_new
Goal:
Plain text
Copy code
1 Create new table with same structure
2 Reuse existing partition function and scheme
3 Copy data in batches
4 Recreate indexes dynamically
5 Validate row counts
6 Swap tables
Step 1 — Identify Existing Partition Metadata
Get partition function and scheme used by the old table.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT 
    t.name AS table_name,
    i.name AS index_name,
    ps.name AS partition_scheme,
    pf.name AS partition_function,
    c.name AS partition_column
FROM sys.tables t
JOIN sys.indexes i 
    ON t.object_id = i.object_id
JOIN sys.partition_schemes ps 
    ON i.data_space_id = ps.data_space_id
JOIN sys.partition_functions pf 
    ON ps.function_id = pf.function_id
JOIN sys.index_columns ic
    ON i.object_id = ic.object_id 
    AND i.index_id = ic.index_id
JOIN sys.columns c
    ON ic.object_id = c.object_id
    AND ic.column_id = c.column_id
WHERE t.name = 'cff_report'
AND ic.partition_ordinal = 1;
This returns:
Plain text
Copy code
partition_function
partition_scheme
partition_column
Step 2 — Generate CREATE TABLE Script Dynamically
Create same table structure without copying data.
SQL
Copy code
DECLARE @sql NVARCHAR(MAX)

SELECT @sql = 'SELECT TOP 0 * INTO dbo.cff_report_new FROM dbo.cff_report'

EXEC sp_executesql @sql
This creates the table structure.
But partitions must be applied manually.
Step 3 — Apply Partition Scheme to New Table
First find the partition scheme.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT ps.name
FROM sys.partition_schemes ps
JOIN sys.indexes i
ON ps.data_space_id = i.data_space_id
JOIN sys.tables t
ON i.object_id = t.object_id
WHERE t.name = 'cff_report'
AND i.index_id <= 1
Then rebuild clustered index on partition scheme.
Example dynamic script:
SQL
Copy code
DECLARE @sql NVARCHAR(MAX)

SELECT @sql =
'CREATE CLUSTERED INDEX CX_cff_report_new 
ON dbo.cff_report_new(report_date)
ON ' + ps.name + '(report_date)'
FROM sys.partition_schemes ps
JOIN sys.indexes i
ON ps.data_space_id = i.data_space_id
JOIN sys.tables t
ON i.object_id = t.object_id
WHERE t.name = 'cff_report'
AND i.index_id = 1

EXEC sp_executesql @sql
Now new table is partitioned.
Step 4 — Dynamically Generate Index Scripts
Copy all indexes from the old table.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT 
'CREATE ' +
CASE WHEN i.is_unique = 1 THEN 'UNIQUE ' ELSE '' END +
i.type_desc + ' INDEX ' + i.name + '_new ON dbo.cff_report_new (' +
STRING_AGG(c.name, ',') + ')'
FROM sys.indexes i
JOIN sys.index_columns ic 
ON i.object_id = ic.object_id 
AND i.index_id = ic.index_id
JOIN sys.columns c
ON ic.object_id = c.object_id
AND ic.column_id = c.column_id
JOIN sys.tables t
ON t.object_id = i.object_id
WHERE t.name = 'cff_report'
AND i.index_id > 1
GROUP BY i.name, i.type_desc, i.is_unique
Save these scripts and run after data load.
Reason:
Plain text
Copy code
Indexes slow down bulk inserts
Step 5 — Batch Data Copy (Critical for 50M rows)
Batching prevents transaction log growth.
Dynamic batch copy script:
SQL
Copy code
DECLARE @BatchSize INT = 50000
DECLARE @Rows INT = 1

WHILE @Rows > 0
BEGIN

INSERT INTO dbo.cff_report_new
SELECT TOP (@BatchSize) *
FROM dbo.cff_report
WHERE report_date NOT IN (
    SELECT report_date FROM dbo.cff_report_new
)

SET @Rows = @@ROWCOUNT

END
Better approach using key range.
Example:
SQL
Copy code
DECLARE @StartDate DATE
DECLARE @EndDate DATE

SELECT @StartDate = MIN(report_date),
       @EndDate = MAX(report_date)
FROM dbo.cff_report

WHILE @StartDate <= @EndDate
BEGIN

INSERT INTO dbo.cff_report_new
SELECT *
FROM dbo.cff_report
WHERE report_date >= @StartDate
AND report_date < DATEADD(DAY,1,@StartDate)

SET @StartDate = DATEADD(DAY,1,@StartDate)

END
This copies partition by partition.
Much faster.
Step 6 — Recreate Indexes on New Table
Execute dynamically generated index scripts.
Example:
SQL
Copy code
CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX IX_cff_report_new_1
ON dbo.cff_report_new(col1, col2)
Step 7 — Validate Data
Check row counts.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT 
(SELECT COUNT(*) FROM dbo.cff_report) AS old_count,
(SELECT COUNT(*) FROM dbo.cff_report_new) AS new_count
Check partitions.
SQL
Copy code
SELECT 
partition_number,
rows
FROM sys.partitions
WHERE object_id = OBJECT_ID('dbo.cff_report_new')
AND index_id <= 1
Step 8 — Rename Tables (Minimal Downtime)
Transaction swap.
SQL
Copy code
BEGIN TRAN

EXEC sp_rename 'dbo.cff_report', 'cff_report_old'

EXEC sp_rename 'dbo.cff_report_new', 'cff_report'

COMMIT
Rollback option exists.
